Hello Bernd

Using Linked List is not suitable for problems
where ou have to access fields in O(1) or
dont want to access them in a row.
If I need a special field I have to search O(n/2) fields.

So dynamic array would be very interesting at
least for me. It does not have to be automatical.
A ReDim command would do it. I could nearly
implement it in Blitz but I dont know how to free
an dimmed Array and I have to write a custom function
for each array I want to use.

The problem is like this:

E.g. I have some wavesamples in my sequencer
program. I have newtypes that keep the information
about the sampledata in an array like the samplefreq,
length and bitresolution.
Now I have to dim it to - lets say - 1024 wavesamples.
This eates a lot of memory for someone who only
wants to use 10 samples or even none. But someone
who does extensive use of samples he may want
more than 1024 samples.
It is like I would pre-allocate the memory for characters in a
texteditor. This is stupid because you dont know how much
text will be written. But I need direct access to
all letters, I dont want to search 1000 letters to find the
1001th one. So I need arrays that can expand (or shrink again).

Another solution is to use a pointer to an array and I use
allocmem and freemem to do this. It would look like this:

NewType.ArrayWrapper
MyArray.MyNewtype[100000000] ; use a high number that will never exceeded. 
End newtype

This should consume only 4 bytes I think.

Then:
*MyBase = allocmem (10*sizeof.MyNewtype)
Then I can use the first 10 entries doing
*MyBase\MyArray[n] = x

This method is not 100% clean because it easy to access
illegal memory because it throws no error message if I do
*MyBase\MyArray[11] = x


Any ideas ?
Ciao,

Thilo


