What kind of container you use for the items is it linked list or array?

If array then fastest in average is quick sort.
It have smaller factor than shell, heap and merge sorts. All of these 
are O(N*log2(N)) though quick sorts worst case is N*N and shell sort 
had something between those two. Merge and heap sort have worst case 
N*log2(N) time requirement.

If lists then merge sort is fastest by mile, because it have smallest 
factor for lists.

merge sort is quite easy to implement for lists first make function 
that will split a list to two equal length lists (well the other might 
be one item longer if the original list have odd number of items). Then 
make a function that will get two lists and merge them by geting always 
the smaller of the two lists first elements and move that to the end of 
the resulting list.

Now the sorting algorythm is simple recursive function

This some kind of pseudo code

list sort(list) {
   if (list_length <2)
     return list;

   list2 = split(list); //will remove half of the "list" and make it as 
new list "list2"

   list  = sort(list);
   list2 = sort(list2);

   list  = merge(list,list2);
   return list;
}

